														<!-- start post -->
					<div class="post-2563 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-personal-finance tag-come tag-first tag-pampered tag-pets" id="post-2563">
					
						<!-- calendar -->
						<div class="calendar">
							<span class="month">Apr</span>
							<span class="day">20</span>
						</div>
						<!-- title of post -->
						  
							<h2 class="title">
								<a href="http://financeeasy.info/2012/04/20/pampered-pets-come-first/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Pampered pets come first">Pampered pets come first</a>
							</h2>
												
						<!-- header-->
						<div class="meta meta-date">
							<span class="meta-info meta-text meta-link">Posted in <a href="http://financeeasy.info/category/personal-finance/" title="View all posts in Personal Finance" rel="category tag">Personal Finance</a></span>
						</div>	
						
						<!-- content  -->								
						<div class="entry">									
														<p>Toronto condo dwellers Martha and Kim are overwhelmed by their investments — two dozen mutual funds, many with overlapping stocks, portfolios with life insurance features sold as segregated funds, a rental condo, and $  3,500 they keep as an emergency reserve to care for a beloved Husky and a calico cat.</p>
<p>Their spending is not the problem, even though the $  650 they lay out each month for things like doggie daycare, veterinary insurance and obedience training is generous. Apart from indulging their pets, Martha and Kim live relatively simply. “We spend the money so that the animals will be able to get out and breathe fresh air every day. It’s the price of being a good pet owner in the urban jungle.”</p>
<p>Martha, 44, is a manager in financial services, and Kim, 41, is a supervisor in a communications company. Together they bring home $  10,500 a month after tax and add about $  250 a month net after-tax income from a condo they rent out for six months of the year, for total monthly disposable income of $  10,750.</p>
<div class="npBlock npRuleMedium npRelated">
<h4 class="npNoRule">Related</h4>
<ul class="npHeadlines">
<li>
<p><a href="http://business.financialpost.com/2012/04/13/caught-in-a-financial-vise/">Caught in a financial vise</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="http://business.financialpost.com/2012/04/10/a-clean-slate/">A Clean Slate</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="http://business.financialpost.com/2012/04/06/can-these-real-estate-agents-afford-to-migrate-toward-retirement/">Can these real estate agents afford to migrate toward retirement?</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="http://business.financialpost.com/2012/04/05/exotic-collectibles-are-hot-but-are-they-worth-the-risk/">Exotic collectibles are hot &#8211; but are they worth the risk?</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="http://business.financialpost.com/2012/04/04/the-big-question-what-to-pay-first/">The big question: what to pay first</a></p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<p><span id="more-165201"></span>Family Finance asked Benoit Poliquin, an Ottawa-based financial planner and portfolio manager, to help Martha and Kim rebalance and simplify their tangled investments.</p>
<p><img class="wp-image-165594 alignleft" title="0420ff" src="http://financialpostbusiness.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/0420ff.jpg?w=319&#038;h=671" alt="" width="319" height="671" />Martha and Kim bought their second condo — valued at $  265,000 with a $  196,000 mortgage — for visiting friends and family, kind of an elaborate guest suite. It has become so popular an idea that their neighbours are renting it for their friends and it is gainfully occupied six months of the year. But the rental income is just sitting in cash rather than paying down the $  58,000 mortgage on the $  285,000 condo they themselves live in or to catch up on unused RRSP space.</p>
<p>The condo earns $  1,500 rent less $  923 mortgage payments and $  100 in other costs. That leaves a net return of $  477 on $  69,000 of equity, 7.3% on just six months income. It’s a decent investment that could appreciate over time, Mr. Poliquin says.</p>
<p>The remainder of their financial assets is a buffet of high-fee mutual funds. Most of Canada’s largest insurance companies and banks have their products represented in the couple’s long list of funds. The reason is in part the previous jobs that Martha and Kim have held. Their employer-sponsored RRSPs have to stay, but the others, souvenirs of their past professional lives, could be shifted to low-fee exchange-traded funds. The saving would shave 2% off about $  200,000 of fund assets, or $  4,000 a year. In 20 years, assuming a 3% after-inflation return, that would build up the startling sum of $  110,706. That alone could add $  3,320 to their pre-tax retirement income. That’s a big reward for cutting complexity and refocusing investment strategy.</p>
<p><strong>Restructuring portfolios</strong></p>
<p>Martha and Kim can adjust their portfolio to have 30% Canadian dividend ETFs, 40% dividend-paying foreign stocks, and 30% Canadian bonds from major corporate issuers, Mr. Poliquin suggests. The largest part of the investments will be inside the couple’s RRSPs. They will not benefit from the dividend tax credit on Canadian-source dividends. On the other hand, they will not be penalized for holding non-Canadian dividend-paying stocks.</p>
<p>Martha and Kim can shop for ETFs that have 10-year investment-grade corporate bonds. They continue to pay yields of 3.3% to 4.5% and, in the 10-year segment of the market, yields are not far from their historical averages, Mr. Poliquin adds. With the help of an investment advisor who can guide them through the complexities of the corporate bond market, the couple could also make direct purchases of a handful of bonds of different issuers. As interest rates rise, the market value of these bonds will drop, but they will pay face value at maturity and will sustain their current or running yields until then.</p>
<p>The question is where to put investments — in RRSPs or TFSAs. If the money goes into RRSPs, it will eventually be paid out as taxable income. TFSA withdrawals are not considered income for tax purposes. If the RRIF payouts together with other income are too large, they may trigger the OAS clawback. TFSA payouts don’t do that. They do not produce taxable income, Mr. Poliquin says.</p>
<p>They will qualify for two CPP benefits of $  11,840 a year payable at age 65 and two OAS pensions payable when each is 67 at $  6,481 a year, all in 2012 dollars. If they can add, as they are doing, $  19,200 a year to RRSPs, for 25 years and achieve a 3% rate of asset growth with the present $  190,700 of RRSPs, TFSAs and a locked-in retirement account (LIRA), their registered investments will have a value of about $  1,099,000 when Kim begins her 66th year.</p>
<p>Paid out at about 6% a year, that investment capital could add $  69,958 to annual income, pushing the total for the couple to about $  106,600 a year before tax. Divided by two, each would have $  53,300 before tax, well below the OAS clawback trigger point in 2012, $  69,562. If taxed at an average 20% rate, they would have $  7,106 a month to spend, 66% of their present disposable income.</p>
<p>“The critical element in this retirement forecast is building up investment income through contributions and asset growth. That takes a commitment which, in time, will produce a substantial return with less than average stock market risk,” Mr. Poliquin says.</p>
<p><em>Need help getting out of a financial fix? Email <a href="mailto:andrewallentuci@mts.net" target="_blank">andrewallentuci@mts.net</a> for a free Family Finance analysis.</em></p>
